794	Tufano's Vernon Park Tap	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nFor more than 80 years, Tufano's Vernon Park Tap has been dishing out old-school Italian dishes. The James Beard award and solid Chicago fan base prove the quality of their classic dishes. The way Guy sees it, their signature lemon chicken is nothing short of a "bodacious bird."\n	\n                  1073 W. Vernon Park Place, Chicago, IL 60607	41.8728013	-87.6540191	testrestaurant_state53	testfood_type53	testepisode_info53
800	The Madison Diner (Formerly Big Star Diner)	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThe Madison Diner on Bainbridge Island, Wash., is an actual New Jersey diner that was shipped all the way to Washington. So it makes sense that the menu includes East Coast diner favorites with a West Coast twist. Check out the Atlantic Salmon Hash and the Guy-approved Chorizo Scramble.\n	\n                  305 Madison Ave. N., Bainbridge Island, WA 98110	47.6267747	-122.5216684	testrestaurant_state53	testfood_type53	testepisode_info53
825	Q Restaurant and Wine Bar	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nA neighborhood diner in the Richmond district of San Francisco, Q Restaurant specializes in "funky, American comfort." Try the Pulled Pork or Funky American-Style Duck Confit, made over 16 days, finished in the deep fryer and served with polenta and asparagus. Guy's take: "So worth it!"\n	\n                  225 Clement Street, San Francisco, CA 94118	37.78285320000001	-122.4616957	testrestaurant_state55	testfood_type55	testepisode_info55
846	Mad Greek Restaurant	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThe middle of the desert might not seem like the best place to open a Greek diner, but the Mad Greek Restaurant has been attracting crowds for over 20 years. Chef Larry Dabour uses his grandmother's recipes for specialties like gyros, spanakopita (spinach pie) and shawarma — Guy's favorite.\n	\n                  72112 Baker Blvd, Baker, CA 92309	35.2659102	-116.0747731	testrestaurant_state56	testfood_type56	testepisode_info56
848	Louie's	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nDrop by Louie's to sample the Don, a burger that Guy says is "super-mondo juicy." The fresh-ground Angus patty is basted with a soy-and-garlic-laced secret sauce, layered with Swiss cheese, bacon and jalapeno, then nestled between slices of rye bread. Also try the thin-crust pizza slathered with crushed tomato sauce and topped with Angus beef-and-pork butt sausage, Wisconsin cheese, onions and green peppers.\n	\n                  1839 N Henderson Ave, Dallas, TX 75206	32.8110912	-96.77451909999999	testrestaurant_state56	testfood_type56	testepisode_info56
851	Leo's BBQ	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nAccording to Chef Charles Smith, the secret to his great tasting barbecue is love. Guy got messy with the spare ribs dripping with the house-made BBQ sauce and loved the hot links. Save some room for dessert, too, because all dinners are served with a free piece of strawberry banana cake.\n	\n                  3631 N Kelley Ave, Oklahoma City 73111	35.5074097	-97.4947069	testrestaurant_state56	testfood_type56	testepisode_info56
854	Johnny Garlic's	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nOnly at Guy's restaurant can you get a little Italian, Mexican, Cajun and Asian. The grilled-onion-and-garlic tortilla stack, inspired by Guy's mom, has "dynamite" texture and flavor. Guy's Sashimi Won Tacos dressed with eel sauce were double gold winners at the Sonoma County Harvest Fair.\n	\n                  10505 Fairway Dr., Roseville 95678	38.7924557	-121.2909334	testrestaurant_state57	testfood_type57	testepisode_info57
855	Joey K's Restaurant & Bar	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nA family-owned eatery located in a charming century-old building, Joey K's is the place to go for "a real taste of Louisiana soul food." Many items on the menu, like the popular Shrimp Magazine, are named after local streets. Also try the classic Red Beans and Rice, Fried Oysters and Jambalaya.\n	\n                  3001 Magazine Street, New Orleans, LA 70115	29.9250792	-90.08484299999999	testrestaurant_state57	testfood_type57	testepisode_info57
856	Joe's Cable Car	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nA burger to us is fresh ground steak to Joe. At Joe's Cable Car, the meat is the star (that and his neon-orama dining room). Fresh chuck is ground daily to attain griddle glory as a patty melt or burger (favorite topper: avocado). Guy's verdict? Big. Juicy. Bananas (contains no actual banana).\n	\n                  4320 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94112	37.7284687	-122.4319268	testrestaurant_state57	testfood_type57	testepisode_info57
869	Harold's Restaurant	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThe recipe for the chili burger (it's really a meatball sandwich) at Harold's Restaurant has remained unchanged for 75 years, and Tony Lipscomb loved it so much that he bought the place. You'll also find pinto beans with fatback (fresh fat from the pig's back) which Guy declared ''off the hook.''\n	\n                  602 N. Limestone St., Gaffney, SC 29340	35.0765425	-81.6460016	testrestaurant_state58	testfood_type58	testepisode_info58
876	Gott's Roadside Tray Gourmet (formerly Taylor's Automatic Refresher)	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nGott's Roadside Tray Gourmet won a James Beard Award for Best American Classic, so it's no surprise this Napa Valley staple serves up amazing hamburgers. The special is the Wisconsin burger, with grilled mushrooms, bacon and melted cheddar cheese. As Guy said, ''It's all about the quality.''\n	\n                  933 Main Street, St. Helena, CA 94574	38.5019171	-122.4654991	testrestaurant_state58	testfood_type58	testepisode_info58
884	Galewood Cookshack	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nOn Food Network's Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives, host Guy Fieri discovers the Gailwood Cook Shack, a BBQ RV in Chicago, IL, that brings North Carolina-style pulled pork to just about anyone in the area.\n	\n                  , Chicago, IL	41.8781136	-87.6297982	testrestaurant_state59	testfood_type59	testepisode_info59
890	Elf's Den Restaurant & Lounge	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nIt's always Christmas at the Elf's Den Restaurant & Lounge. Chef Tony Ysais' North Pole workshop is out of toys, playing instead with homemade rolls and Reindeer Sausage Hoagies. Guy insists that you open wide for the Almond-Crusted Beef Tournedo with bearnaise and gravy more than just once a year.\n	\n                  2556 Mistletoe Rd, North Pole, AK 99705	64.7507677	-147.3283171	testrestaurant_state59	testfood_type59	testepisode_info59
895	Donnie Mac's Trailer Park Cuisine	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nGuy Fieri, host of Food Network's Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives, uncovers Donnie Mac's Trailer Park Cuisine in Boise, ID, a tire store turned diner where they'll put just about anything in their mac and cheese.\n	\n                  1515 W. Grove St., Boise, ID 83702	43.6191305	-116.2133095	testrestaurant_state59	testfood_type59	testepisode_info59
905	Country Cafe	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThe North Pole's Country Cafe has enough holiday giddyup for all nine reindeer. Guy was ready for a long winter's nap after polishing off their butter-basted Turkey Dinner with homemade stuffing. Eating local? Order the Cranberry-Glazed Ham, lacquered with wild Alaskan cranberry sauce.\n	\n                  235 North Santa Claus Ln., North Pole, AK 99705	64.755965	-147.3541032	testrestaurant_state60	testfood_type60	testepisode_info60
919	Brint's Diner - UNDER NEW OWNERSHIP	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nBrint's Diner in Wichita may have been remodeled recently, but it hasn't lost the warm and down-to-earth atmosphere (no big-screen TV, just food and folks) that's kept locals coming back for more. Guy was particularly impressed with the scrambled eggs, which were light, fluffy and not oily.\n	\n                  4834 E. Lincoln Street, Wichita, KS 67216	37.6728448	-97.2792262	testrestaurant_state61	testfood_type61	testepisode_info61
926	Blow Fly Inn	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nEvery dish at Blow Fly Inn is topped with a fly. Don't be alarmed, as the fly is tiny, plastic and has become a signature garnish at the Blow Fly Inn. When Guy swung by, he looked past the fly and dove right into the bayou classics, including smoked sausage and Blow Fly's gumbo made with okra.\n	\n                  1201 Washington Ave, Gulfport 39507	30.403787	-89.031419	testrestaurant_state61	testfood_type61	testepisode_info61
962	Penguin Drive-In - CLOSED	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nMost people enjoy some french fries or onion rings with a burger, but how about fried pickles? The regulars at the Penguin in North Carolina can't get enough of them. Head Chef Greg Auten makes his corn dogs from scratch, and Guy got addicted to his pimento grilled cheese.\n	\n                  1921 Commonwealth Ave., Charlotte, NC 28205	35.2189571	-80.81243049999999	testrestaurant_state64	testfood_type64	testepisode_info64
969	Bar-B-Q King	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nWhat flows through the river of Flavortown? Guy says it's the Bar-B-Q Chicken at Bar-B-Q King. On The Best Thing I Ever Ate and Triple D, he chows down on their chicken that's been fried and then dunked in their famous barbecue sauce. It's nothing short of a tried-and-true recipe from 1959.\n	\n                  2900 Wilkinson Blvd., Charlotte, NC 28208	35.224468	-80.8891117	testrestaurant_state64	testfood_type64	testepisode_info64
999	The Depot Diner	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThe Depot Diner is operating under new ownership since Triple D stopped there, but don't worry about missing out on Thanksgiving flavors with that famous turkey sandwich because they're still making it the same way. Come ready to eat with your hands and use lots of napkins.\n	\n                  5840 W Roosevelt Rd, Chicago, IL 60644	41.8657517	-87.7708679	testrestaurant_state66	testfood_type66	testepisode_info66
1012	Squeeze Burger (formerly Squeeze Inn)	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThis tiny burger joint is short on space, but customers pack in for favorites like the Squeezeburger with Cheese. A 1/3-pound patty is heaped with so much cheese (more than half a pound) that the topping forms a crisp skirt of sorts after a turn on the flat top. “That thing is money,” said Guy of the cheese-blanketed burger, which comes topped with dill pickles, tomatoes, mustard and mayonnaise.\n	\n                  5301 Power Inn Rd, Sacramento, CA 95820	38.5267125	-121.4085748	testrestaurant_state67	testfood_type67	testepisode_info67
1016	The Village Cafe	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nOn Triple D, Guy described The Village Cafe as "part dive, part bar, but all neighborhood joint." Since 1956 they've been churning out a little of all three with "crunchy crunch" ale-battered onion rings and Italian classics like stromboli stuffed with ham, salami, mozzarella and green peppers.\n	\n                  1001 W. Grace St., Richmond, VA 23220	37.5508706	-77.4534061	testrestaurant_state67	testfood_type67	testepisode_info67
1017	Mama's 39th Street	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nGuy Fieri visits one of America's greatest breakfast joints, Mama's 39th Street, in Kansas City, MO, for some outrageous homemade hash and 60 different omelets on Food Network's Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives.\n	\n                  3906 Waddell St., Kansas City, MO 64111	39.056641	-94.5958714	testrestaurant_state67	testfood_type67	testepisode_info67
1019	Aunt Lena's Creamery	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\n\n	\n                  404 S. Arizona Ave., Chandler, AZ 85248	33.2967084	-111.8421947	testrestaurant_state68	testfood_type68	testepisode_info68
1032	Earl's Drive-In	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nJoin host Guy Fieri, of Food Network's Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives, at Earl's Drive-In in Chaffee, NY, a 42-year-old restaurant next to a farm, where they're serving old school American classics.\n	\n                  12139 Olean Rd. at Rt 16, Chaffee, NY 14030	42.5296275	-78.4786313	testrestaurant_state69	testfood_type69	testepisode_info69
1059	Metro Diner	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nGuy's right when he says Metro Diner "is not your typical diner." They're changing our landscape of comfort food by serving a layer of french fries atop steak salad. Even their French toast is layered with a banana-cream cheese filling smothered between two slices of challah.\n	\n                  3302 Hendricks Ave, Jacksonville, FL 32207	30.2911209	-81.64886729999999	testrestaurant_state70	testfood_type70	testepisode_info70
1061	The General Store	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nHost of Food Network's Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives, Guy Fieri, discovers The General Store in Silver Spring, MD, a 19th century post office turned restaurant cranking out American standards like corndogs and chicken 'n waffles.\n	\n                  6 Post Office Road, Silver Spring, MD 20910	39.0151597	-77.0555736	testrestaurant_state70	testfood_type70	testepisode_info70
1139	Defonte's Sandwich Shop, Manhattan	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nSince 1922, this multigenerational old-school Italian deli in Brooklyn has been a local staple. Guy adored the tender steak pizzaiola with fresh mozzarella in the Sinatra Special. He called the thinly sliced roast beef, fried eggplant and mozzarella sandwich ridiculous and the real deal.\n	\n                  261 Third Ave, New York, NY 10010	40.737325	-73.983881	testrestaurant_state76	testfood_type76	testepisode_info76
1151	Michigan Brewing Co.	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nOn Food Network's Diners, Drive-Ins and Dives, Kid Rock takes Guy Fieri on a thirst-quenching tour of Michigan Brewing Co. in Webberville, MI.\n	\n                  1093 Highview Dr, Webberville, MI 48892	42.6616227	-84.19444399999999	testrestaurant_state76	testfood_type76	testepisode_info76
1164	Harvey's Hot Dogs II	static/img/attachment-guys-diner-background.jpg	\nThis old-school local hangout is pumping out hot dogs and Southern comfort food. The tender dumplings and the rich and creamy flavor of the chicken and dumpling soup captured Guy’s heart. Locals enjoy the chili dogs as well as the subs and barbecue.\n	\n                  3205 Stamford Rd., Portsmouth, VA 23703	36.86093570000001	-76.39068739999999	testrestaurant_state77	testfood_type77	testepisode_info77
